  "prompt": "What is the relation between phase and line voltage?",
  "response": "The relationship between phase voltage and line voltage depends on whether the electrical system is a star (Y) or delta (\u0394) configuration. \n\n1. **Star (Y) Configuration:**\n   - In a star configuration, the line voltage (V_L) is \u221a3 times the phase voltage (V_Ph).\n   - Mathematically, this relationship is given by: \\( V_L = \\sqrt{3} \\times V_Ph \\).\n   - Example: If the phase voltage is 230V, the line voltage will be \\( V_L = \\sqrt{3} \\times 230V \u2248 398V \\).\n\n2. **Delta (\u0394) Configuration:**\n   - In a delta configuration, the line voltage (V_L) is equal to the phase voltage (V_Ph).\n   - Mathematically, this relationship is given by: \\( V_L = V_Ph \\).\n   - Example: If the phase voltage is 230V, then the line voltage will also be 230V.\n\nTo summarize:\n- **Star (Y) Configuration:**\n  \\( V_L = \\sqrt{3} \\times V_Ph \\)\n- **Delta (\u0394) Configuration:**\n  \\( V_L = V_Ph \\)\n\nThese relationships are fundamental in understanding three-phase electrical systems and are crucial for applications such as designing electrical networks and calculating power distribution.",
